sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Westminster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> our recent book </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Carbon Management in the Built Environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and through our professional networks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat ener</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">gy demand?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government would be wise to recognise and respond to the different challenges posed by generating and distributing renewable heat compared to renewable electricity. In addition, heat needs to be treated as a waste product as well as somethi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng to be generated. As for electricity, there is huge potential in small and community scale generation, however ther</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e is also the need to introduce legislation to ensure waste heat is captured and recycled to local communities. This requires the Governmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t to expand its approach to enable investment in the installation of new infrastructure to connect heat sources to households and local businesses, and could significantly reduce energy demand for heating. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What progress is the government making on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">reduci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ng the demand for heat?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is little evidence to suggest that the UK's heat demand is being significantly reduced by government policy beyond existing regulatory measures, principally the Building Regulations. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC's own analyses rightly point to the r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ole of the recession as a principle factor in the decline observed since 2008, whilst final energy consumption has rarely dipped below 140,000 thousand tonnes of oil equivalent since 1970, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is good agreement when these figures are adjusted for the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> impact of temperature on energy demand.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives. What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his is a high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly contested issue that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in our view,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has not yet been adequately resolved. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Initiative for Carbon (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ICARB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in which GCU is a partner,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has previously issued an official statement here: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">http://icarb.org/2012/11/28/is-biomass-really-dirtier-than-coal/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are significant concerns over the sustainability of large scale biomass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and over the sufficiency of the FSC label in ensuring all biomass is sustainably sourced. Given the qua</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntities of wood expected to be used for biomass the 70% lower limit for FSC certification needs to become 100%, and stricter policing of overseas suppliers is needed. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Dr Baker has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">confidential written</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> evidence on this to the Scottish Government w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hich could be made available to this inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Longer-term, biomass can only be considered sustainable if demand for fuel can be met from within the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> limits to the level of demand that can be met from sustainable sources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mean that policies on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use of biomass should prioritise small to medium-scale CHP and district heating projects. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Well-designed CHP-based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> district heating schemes should have no notable environmental impacts providing the buildings and sites selected for the CHP units</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are sufficiently ventilated and exposed to disperse emissions, particularly particulates from biomass CHP. However there are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> legitimate concerns over the impact of unabated emissions from large scale biomass, and over the use of individual domestic biomass CHP units in dense urban areas, where the 'canyoning effect' can concentrate emissions and impact on air quality.    </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">      </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The most significant risks for continuing the reliance on gas for space heating are security of supply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and future price rises. Alastair Buchanan, the out-going head of Ofgem, illustrates the vulnerability of UK gas supplies in his talk on Ofgem's Project Discovery (see: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">http://www.ofgem.gov.uk/Media/keyspeeches/Pages/security-of-supply.aspx</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This and oth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er evidence shows that the UK is already vulnerable to interruptions and price rises, and therefore it is reasonable to recommend a transition away from using gas directly for space heating, however this needs to be supported by increased renewable electri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">city generation to match, and outpace, this fuel shift. (See also Baker et al., 2012).    </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The critical problems are a lack of investment in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> retrofitting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and a lack of regulation to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensure that new housing is connected to CHP infrastructure, and to require the owners of new sources of waste heat to install infrastructure to distribute that heat to local homes and businesses. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The first problem requires the Government to give consist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent and long-term signals to the energy industry, supported by local decision-making, to enable the industry to expand heating infrastructure and make it flexible enough to deliver a range of heating fluids (biogas, steam, etc).  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second problem could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be resolved by the introduction of a Heat Planning Law to ensure waste heat is recovered and recycled to local homes and businesses. This could be introduced through the existing planning  system, and could have the additional benefit of reducing emission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s from transport through encouraging co-location of housing and employment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These issues and recommendations are detailed in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Housing Futures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report (Baker, Emmanuel &amp; Phillipson, 2012).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However there are also some significant untapped opportunities f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or developing alternative sources of community heating, for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">example using flooded mineworkings (see: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">http://www.gcu.ac.uk/newsevents/news/article.php?id=53804</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> )</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Figures co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mpiled as part of our work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Emmanuel &amp; Baker, 2012) give approximate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">costs for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual domestic installations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: £2,000-£4,000 fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r solar thermal; £8,000-£17,000 for ground source heat pumps; £5,000 to £10,000 for air source heat pumps; and approximately £3,000 for individual CHP units. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Based on our experience of working with local authori</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ties and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">housing associations, it is the variability and uncertainty in payback periods, rather than the length of the payback period, that discourages investment. However these uncertainties can be significantly reduced by careful technology choice supported by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cupant education.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Here again, retrofitting infrastructure should be seen as ke</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y to enabling these technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example by enabling CHP and GSHP community heating to be supplemented by building-integrated solar thermal and ASHPs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The long term aim shou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld be capture and distribute or store all 'waste' heat from the built environment. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">    </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many experts expect overheating to become a significant problem for the UK as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">climate change progresses, however overheating can be predicted and buildings can be designed to minimise it (e.g. see CIBSE, 2013). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An Expert Workshop convened by ClimateXChange Scotland (Beckmann, 2013) concluded that the most significant barrier to ad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">apting the building stock to a warmer climate is the lack of an enabling environment. The report contains a list of 20 recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> made by the experts, who included the renowned architect Bill Gething and representatives from Scotland's leading built e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nvironment research groups.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Installing heat pumps at a community scale (e.g. a community ground source heat pump) entails overcoming a range of barriers, including meeting planning law requir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ements, raising finance, and engaging with local government, delivery partners, and end-users.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However the knock-on benefits of supporting community scale heat pumps are naturally more wide-ranging.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Take up of individual heat pump systems should largely r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eflect household awareness and preference. A suggestion here is that, whilst households may be less aware of heat pumps, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the substantial academic evidence on the comparative benefits of solar thermal (e.g. Roaf et al., 2012) is being supported by consumer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">preference.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Heat pumps also come in a variety of forms and vary significantly in scale, from small building-mounted ASHPs to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">large and innovative uses of the technology, for example exploiting flooded mineworkings in Glasgow (see: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">http://www.gcu.ac.uk/newsevents/news/article.php?id=53804</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ). The RHI needs to be extended and made more flexible to better capture all these potential applications.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">11.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Enrolment in the RHI req</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uires a Green Deal assessment, which requires an up-front fee and associates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the RHI with a much-criticised,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and (to date) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relatively </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unsuccessful initiative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It seems reasonable to expect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that this will hamper its take up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to some extent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Thermal storag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually. What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">12.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Building Regulations in place across the UK currently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disincentivise designers to use high thermal mass solutions to reduce and regulate heating energy demand, and to use natural ventilation systems (as opposed to the mechanical ventilation used in the PassivHaus system).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Whilst both approaches are valid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">grea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ter flexibility needs to be introduced to enable natural heating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, cooling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and ventilation solutions can compete with mechanical solutions, and without relaxing emissions reduction goals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (e.g. see CIBSE, 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; Roaf, 2012; &amp; Humphreys et al. 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Baker, K.J., Emmanuel, R., &amp; Phillipson, M., 2012. Support for RPP2 - Housing Futures. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Available at: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0038/00389071.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Beckmann, 2013.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Workshop Report: Climate Resilience for the Scottish Built Environment. ClimateXChange Scotland. Available a